@page "/faq"

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- HERO (dark green) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="hero">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>
        <p>
            This FAQ explains the concepts behind Ripple and aquaponics as they are presented in this 
            college honors project. Ripple is a proof‑of‑concept model, not an active organization, 
            facility, or food distribution program.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-coral"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- GENERAL QUESTIONS (pale coral) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="pale-coral">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2><i class="fa-solid fa-circle-question"></i> General Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What is Ripple?</h3>
            <p>
                Ripple is a conceptual aquaponics‑based nonprofit model created for a college honors 
                project. It explores how sustainable, community‑focused food systems could operate in 
                the Chicagoland area, but it is not currently implemented in real life.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What is aquaponics?</h3>
            <p>
                Aquaponics grows fish and plants together in a closed‑loop system. Fish produce nutrients 
                for the plants, and the plants clean the water for the fish. In this project, aquaponics 
                is used as a theoretical framework for sustainable food production.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-blue"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- FOOD & DISTRIBUTION (pale blue) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="pale-blue">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2><i class="fa-solid fa-apple-whole"></i> Food & Distribution (Conceptual)</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Is the food free?</h3>
            <p>
                In this project model, all produce and fish are imagined as being distributed through 
                local food pantries and community partners at no cost. This reflects how a real nonprofit 
                might operate, but no food is actually being grown or distributed.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What kinds of food do you grow?</h3>
            <p>
                The project models the production of buttercrisp lettuce and other leafy greens, along 
                with Nile tilapia. These choices reflect common real‑world aquaponic crops but are used 
                here for educational and conceptual purposes only.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Where does the food go?</h3>
            <p>
                In the conceptual model, food is distributed to Chicagoland food pantries and community 
                organizations. This distribution network is hypothetical and part of the academic design.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-coral"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- FACILITY & SAFETY (dark green) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="why-aquaponics">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2><i class="fa-solid fa-shield-heart"></i> Facility & Safety (Modeled)</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Is the facility safe and clean?</h3>
            <p>
                The project describes a facility that follows strict biosecurity practices, daily water 
                testing, and separate zones for fish, plants, and packaging. These details represent how 
                a real aquaponics facility would operate, but no physical facility exists for this project.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Do you use chemicals or pesticides?</h3>
            <p>
                In the modeled system, no chemical fertilizers or pesticides are used. Aquaponics relies 
                on natural nutrient cycles and beneficial bacteria. This reflects real‑world practices but 
                is presented here conceptually.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Can I tour the facility?</h3>
            <p>
                Since Ripple is a conceptual project, there is no physical facility to tour. However, the 
                website outlines how tours and workshops might function in a real implementation.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-blue"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- VOLUNTEERING & EDUCATION (pale coral) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="pale-coral">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2><i class="fa-solid fa-people-group"></i> Volunteering & Education (Conceptual)</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Do I need experience to volunteer?</h3>
            <p>
                In the project model, volunteers would be welcome regardless of experience and would help 
                with planting, harvesting, packaging, cleaning, and outreach. These roles are hypothetical 
                and part of the educational design.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Can students or researchers work with Ripple?</h3>
            <p>
                Yes — conceptually. The project imagines collaboration with students, educators, and 
                researchers interested in sustainability, biology, engineering, or community impact. 
                These opportunities are not active but represent how a real nonprofit might operate.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Do you offer workshops?</h3>
            <p>
                Workshops are described as part of the conceptual model to illustrate how community 
                education could be integrated into a real aquaponics program.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-coral"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- SUPPORT & DONATIONS (pale blue) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="pale-blue">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2><i class="fa-solid fa-hand-holding-heart"></i> Support & Donations (Demonstration Only)</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>How can I support Ripple?</h3>
            <p>
                In this honors project, support is conceptual. The site outlines ways people could get 
                involved — such as volunteering, attending workshops, or donating — to demonstrate how a 
                real nonprofit might engage its community.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Are donations tax‑deductible?</h3>
            <p>
                Ripple is described as a future 501(c)(3) nonprofit for demonstration purposes only. 
                It is not legally registered, and no real donations are being collected.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>
